{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/hyponatraemia/background-information/pathophysiology/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"336f0b50-af95-5811-8819-05ebe4104ffb","slug":"pathophysiology","fullItemName":"Pathophysiology","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field a7f65c1a-da0f-4ff7-b420-a76900acec60 --><h2>What is the pathophysiology of hyponatraemia?</h2><!-- end field a7f65c1a-da0f-4ff7-b420-a76900acec60 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item b8f48b7f-a0af-4973-afb7-a76900acea9a --><!-- begin field 0b9895ff-38dd-489a-a846-a76900acec60 --><ul><li><strong>Hyponatraemia results from a relative excess of body water to sodium.</strong><ul><li>Serum sodium concentration is determined by serum water content. Serum water increases with water intake (driven by thirst or habit) and decreases through insensible losses (for example sweating) and urinary dilution [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">Reynolds, 2006</a>].</li><li>Urinary dilution is regulated mainly by the antidiuretic hormone (ADH) also known as vasopressin [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">GAIN, 2010</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">Spasovski, 2014</a>]. ADH is produced by the hypothalamus and then stored in and released from the posterior pituitary gland. It increases the reabsorption of water by the kidney and prevents excessive loss of water from the body.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Hyponatraemia is usually associated with a disturbance in ADH secretion [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">Sahay, 2014</a>].</strong><ul><li>ADH disturbances can be physiological (for example hypovolaemia), pathological (for example heart failure), or iatrogenic (for example use of thiazide diuretics) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">Achinger, 2010</a>].</li><li>In most cases of hyponatraemia, there is an inability to suppress ADH. However, in rare cases, ADH is suppressed but there is either excess water intake (<a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/background-information/causes/#additional-information-on-causes\">primary polydipsia</a>) or a reduced threshold for the release of ADH (<a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/background-information/causes/#additional-information-on-causes\">reset osmostat syndrome</a>) that impairs renal excretion of excess water [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/references/\">Spasovski, 2014</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>The underlying mechanism leading to hyponatraemia depends on the underlying <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hyponatraemia/background-information/causes/\">cause</a>.</strong></li></ul><!-- end field 0b9895ff-38dd-489a-a846-a76900acec60 --><!-- end item b8f48b7f-a0af-4973-afb7-a76900acea9a -->","topic":{"id":"0a0a0516-fca2-530d-88cd-096861572e3a","topicId":"560440de-b2ae-4ea7-9fb2-a701015e193f","topicName":"Hyponatraemia","slug":"hyponatraemia","lastRevised":"Last revised in November 2020","chapters":[{"id":"2d0342b8-1d8f-5b76-af1d-5c62137a465c","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"94ef9729-defa-5118-80c3-603843005f8a","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"0e655e55-4b6c-5ca3-9d0a-bcf5afa498d8","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"262d0445-6fa5-53ed-8b8c-037da1983e4f","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"f79882a4-6b50-5264-a45b-2d43249a3418","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"8705184f-c0